1. PURPOSE

This document establishes the standard operating procedures for performing comprehensive urinalysis testing at Kaiser Permanente Largo Laboratory using the Sysmex UN-Series integrated automated urinalysis solution. This includes the UC-3500 automated urine chemistry analyzer and UF-5000 flow cytometry analyzer. This SOP ensures accurate, reliable, and clinically meaningful urinalysis results for diagnosis and monitoring of renal, urinary tract, and systemic diseases.

Core Objectives:

  • Standardize urinalysis testing procedures across all shifts
  • Ensure compliance with CLIA, CAP, and Joint Commission requirements
  • Provide accurate results for diagnosis and monitoring of renal and systemic diseases
  • Maintain quality standards for all aspects of urinalysis testing
  • Support clinical decision-making with timely and reliable results

Definitions

  • UDM: Urinalysis Data Manager - The integrated software system that manages and reviews urinalysis results from both the CLINITEK Novus and UF-5000 analyzers
  • LPF: Low Power Field (10X objective)
  • HPF: High Power Field (40X objective)
  • QC: Quality Control
  • LIS: Laboratory Information System
  • STAT: Immediately; urgent priority
  • QNS: Quantity Not Sufficient
  • CLINITEK Novus: Automated urine chemistry analyzer
  • UF-5000: Automated urine particle analyzer using flow cytometry
  • Sysmex UN-2000: Integrated urinalysis solution combining chemistry and microscopy analyzers

2. CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE

Urinalysis provides essential diagnostic information about renal function, urinary tract infections, metabolic disorders, and systemic diseases. The test combines physical, chemical, and microscopic examinations to deliver comprehensive insights.

Clinical Applications:

Parameter Clinical Significance Associated Conditions
Protein Kidney function indicator Glomerulonephritis, pre-eclampsia, diabetic nephropathy
Glucose Metabolic status Diabetes mellitus, gestational diabetes, renal glycosuria
Blood/RBC Urinary tract integrity UTI, kidney stones, glomerular disease, trauma
WBC/Leukocyte esterase Infection marker UTI, pyelonephritis, interstitial nephritis
Nitrite Bacterial presence Bacterial UTI (gram-negative organisms)
Ketones Metabolic status Diabetic ketoacidosis, starvation, fasting
Bilirubin Liver function Hepatitis, cirrhosis, biliary obstruction
Specific Gravity Concentration ability Dehydration, diabetes insipidus, SIADH
pH Acid-base status Renal tubular acidosis, UTI, metabolic disorders
Casts Kidney pathology Glomerulonephritis, acute tubular necrosis, pyelonephritis

3. SCOPE

This procedure applies to all Medical Laboratory Technicians (MLTs) and Medical Laboratory Scientists (MLSs) trained and competent in the use of the Sysmex UN-Series analyzers (UC-3500 and UF-5000) for performing urinalysis testing on patient specimens at Kaiser Permanente Largo Laboratory.

Personnel Covered:

  • Medical Laboratory Scientists (MLS) - ASCP or AMT certified
  • Medical Laboratory Technicians (MLT) - ASCP or AMT certified
  • Laboratory Assistants (for specimen processing only)
  • Pathology residents and fellows under supervision

Testing Covered:

  • Routine urinalysis (UA)
  • Urine microscopy
  • Urine culture screen
  • Special stains and procedures as ordered

4. RESPONSIBILITIES

Medical Laboratory Scientist/Technician

  • Perform daily QC and document results
  • Process urine specimens according to protocol
  • Perform microscopic examination when indicated
  • Report critical values immediately
  • Maintain instrument cleanliness and perform daily maintenance
  • Troubleshoot analytical problems

Lead Technologist

  • Review QC data and take corrective action as needed
  • Ensure staff competency and training
  • Coordinate instrument maintenance and repairs
  • Investigate discrepant results
  • Update procedures as needed

Laboratory Director

  • Overall responsibility for test quality and compliance
  • Review and approve procedures
  • Ensure regulatory compliance
  • Review proficiency testing results

5. SAFETY REQUIREMENTS

⚠️ Universal Precautions Required

  • Treat all urine specimens as potentially infectious
  • Wear appropriate PPE: gloves, lab coat, safety glasses when splashing possible
  • No eating, drinking, or applying cosmetics in work areas
  • Wash hands after removing gloves and before leaving work area

Chemical Safety

  • Review SDS for all reagents before use
  • Store reagents according to manufacturer specifications
  • Use fume hood when working with volatile chemicals
  • Properly dispose of chemical waste

Biological Safety

  • Use biological safety cabinet for aerosol-generating procedures
  • Decontaminate work surfaces with 10% bleach or approved disinfectant
  • Dispose of specimens in biohazard containers
  • Report all exposures immediately to supervisor and employee health

6. SPECIMEN REQUIREMENTS

Preferred Specimen

  • Type: Random clean-catch midstream urine
  • Volume: Minimum 12 mL (ideal 20-50 mL)
  • Container: Sterile urine container with secure lid
  • Preservative: None for routine; BD Vacutainer® C&S Preservative for delayed testing

Collection Instructions

Female Patients:

  1. Wash hands thoroughly
  2. Separate labia and cleanse with antiseptic wipes (front to back)
  3. Begin urinating into toilet
  4. Collect midstream portion in container
  5. Complete urination into toilet
  6. Secure lid tightly

Male Patients:

  1. Wash hands thoroughly
  2. Retract foreskin if uncircumcised
  3. Cleanse glans with antiseptic wipes
  4. Begin urinating into toilet
  5. Collect midstream portion in container
  6. Secure lid tightly

Specimen Handling

Storage Condition Maximum Time Comments
Room temperature 2 hours Ideal for immediate testing
Refrigerated (2-8°C) 24 hours May cause crystal precipitation
With preservative 72 hours at RT Not for culture if preservative used

Rejection Criteria:

  • Specimen >2 hours old at room temperature without preservative
  • Contamination with feces or toilet paper
  • Insufficient volume (<12 mL)
  • Unlabeled or mislabeled specimen
  • Wrong container type for ordered test
  • Visible contamination or deterioration

9. MAINTENANCE

Daily Maintenance - Sysmex UN-Series

UC-3500 Daily Maintenance:

  1. Check reagent levels and expiration dates
  2. Clean sample probe and work area
  3. Empty waste container
  4. Run background check
  5. Perform daily QC

UF-5000 Daily Maintenance:

  1. Check all reagent levels (sheath, diluent, stain)
  2. Clean sample probe with CELLCLEAN
  3. Check waste levels
  4. Run background count
  5. Perform daily calibration check

Weekly Maintenance

  1. Clean strip waste container
  2. Clean sample area thoroughly
  3. Check and clean barcode reader
  4. Perform system cleaning cycle

Monthly Maintenance

  1. Replace sample probe tubing
  2. Clean ventilation filters
  3. Calibrate specific gravity if needed
  4. Review and archive maintenance logs

10. QUALITY CONTROL REQUIREMENTS

QC Frequency Requirements

  • Daily: Run both positive and negative controls
  • Each shift: If >8 hours since last QC
  • After maintenance: Before patient testing resumes
  • New lot/shipment: Parallel testing with old lot

QC Procedure - Sysmex UN-Series

UC-3500 QC Procedure:

  1. Allow UC Control Level 1 & 2 to reach room temperature (15 minutes)
  2. Mix gently by inversion 8-10 times
  3. Run both levels at start of each shift
  4. Verify all chemistry parameters are within ±2 SD
  5. Document in LIS QC module

UF-5000 QC Procedure:

  1. Run UF Control at start of each shift
  2. Verify cell counts are within acceptable ranges
  3. Check coefficient of variation (CV) < 10%
  4. Review scattergrams for proper population separation
  5. Document results in QC log

Integrated System Checks:

  1. Verify UC-UF correlation for specific gravity
  2. Check auto-verification rules are functioning
  3. Confirm data transmission to LIS

Acceptable QC Ranges - Sysmex UN-Series

UC-3500 Control Ranges:

Parameter Level 1 (Normal) Level 2 (Abnormal)
pH 6.0 ± 0.5 7.5 ± 0.5
Specific Gravity 1.015 ± 0.005 1.025 ± 0.005
Protein Negative to Trace 2+ to 3+
Glucose Negative 2+ to 4+
Ketones Negative 1+ to 2+
Blood Negative to Trace 2+ to 3+
Nitrite Negative Positive
Leukocyte esterase Negative 2+ to 3+

UF-5000 Control Ranges:

Parameter Expected Range (per µL) CV Acceptable
RBC Target ± 20% < 10%
WBC Target ± 20% < 10%
Bacteria Target ± 25% < 15%
Epithelial Cells Target ± 25% < 15%
Casts Qualitative assessment N/A

QC Failure Actions:

  1. Do not report patient results
  2. Repeat QC with fresh aliquot
  3. If still fails, check reagent expiration and storage
  4. Perform maintenance if indicated
  5. Run calibration if available
  6. Contact supervisor if unresolved
  7. Document all corrective actions

11. CALIBRATION

Sysmex UN-Series Calibration

UC-3500 Calibration:
  • Automatic calibration with each new lot of test strips
  • Enter lot information when loading new strips
  • System performs automatic calibration
  • Verify with QC before patient testing
UF-5000 Calibration:
  • Factory calibrated - no user calibration required
  • Daily background counts serve as calibration verification
  • Annual service includes full calibration check
  • Use UF calibrator for troubleshooting only

Refractometer Calibration (Backup Method)

  1. Clean prism with distilled water
  2. Apply 2-3 drops of distilled water
  3. Adjust to read 1.000 specific gravity
  4. Test with known specific gravity solutions
  5. Document calibration in log

Documentation and Retention Requirements

[Reference: KP SOP 15141_1 Section 6.12 and Anatomic Pathology Retention Policies]

Quality Control Data Retention:

  • Commercial controls and instrument data: Retain for 2 years as per Anatomic Pathology: Retention of Records and Materials
  • Printing QC Data:
    • Select appropriate option to print graphs
    • Select option to print raw data
    • Select file option to save data to removable media

Export and Documentation Requirements

[Reference: KP SOP 15141_1 Section 6.17.1]

⚠️ Critical: Current instrument settings and rules must be exported and saved on external storage device each time a change is made. A printout of the settings should be inserted in the instrument Resource Manual.

Documentation Requirements Include:

Document Type Retention Period Storage Location
QC Results 2 years LIS and paper backup
Calibration Records 2 years Instrument log book
Maintenance Logs 2 years Instrument log book
Patient Results 7 years LIS archive
Instrument Settings Current + previous version External storage + manual
Proficiency Testing 2 years PT file cabinet
Best Practices for Documentation:
  • Perform daily backup of QC data to external storage
  • Print monthly QC summary reports for paper backup
  • Export instrument settings quarterly or after any changes
  • Maintain both electronic and paper records when possible
  • Ensure all documentation is legible and complete
  • Document all corrective actions taken for QC failures
  • Record lot numbers and expiration dates for all reagents and controls

12. TROUBLESHOOTING

Common Issues and Solutions

Problem Possible Cause Solution
Strip read error Dirty optics Clean optical system per manual
QC repeatedly fails Expired/deteriorated controls Use fresh controls, check storage
Inconsistent results Improper mixing Ensure proper specimen mixing
No aspiration Clogged probe Clean or replace probe
False positive blood Contamination Check for cleanser contamination
High blank readings Contaminated reagents Replace reagents, clean system

13. TEST PROCEDURE

Physical Examination

  1. Color: Note and record (straw, yellow, amber, red, brown, etc.)
  2. Clarity: Clear, hazy, cloudy, turbid
  3. Odor: Note unusual odors (fruity, foul, ammonia)

Chemical Analysis - Sysmex UC-3500

  1. Mix specimen gently by inversion (8-10 times)
  2. Pour minimum 2 mL into UC tube
  3. Place in UC-3500 sample rack
  4. Ensure proper barcode reading
  5. Analyzer automatically aspirates sample
  6. Results transmitted to UDM for review

Particle Analysis - Sysmex UF-5000

  1. Sample automatically transferred from UC-3500 (if integrated)
  2. For manual mode: Pour minimum 2 mL into UF tube
  3. Flow cytometry analysis performed automatically
  4. Counts RBC, WBC, bacteria, epithelial cells, casts, crystals
  5. Results with scattergrams displayed in UDM
  6. Auto-verification rules applied

Microscopic Examination

When to Perform:

  • Positive blood or protein
  • Positive leukocyte esterase or nitrite
  • Physician request
  • Abnormal color or clarity

Procedure:

  1. Pour 10-12 mL urine into conical tube
  2. Centrifuge at 400 × g (1500 RPM) for 5 minutes
  3. Decant supernatant, leaving ~0.5-1.0 mL
  4. Resuspend sediment by gentle mixing
  5. Place drop on slide and coverslip
  6. Examine under microscope:
    • 10× for casts and overall scan
    • 40× for detailed examination
  7. Report average number per field:

Microscopic Reporting Guidelines

Element Low Power Field (10×) High Power Field (40×)
RBC - 0-2/hpf normal
WBC - 0-5/hpf normal
Epithelial cells - Few, moderate, many
Casts Report type and #/lpf -
Crystals - Report type and quantity
Bacteria - Few, moderate, many
Yeast - Present/absent

⚠️ Critical QC Rule:

NEVER report patient results if QC is not acceptable. Patient safety depends on accurate results. If QC fails, troubleshoot and repeat. If still failing, use backup method or send to reference lab.

Follow-up Notification Requirements:

  1. Immediately notify Lead Technologist of QC failure
  2. Document all troubleshooting steps attempted
  3. Contact Sysmex Tech Support and obtain reference number
  4. Notify Technical Quality Specialist with:
    • All troubleshooting steps performed
    • Tech support reference number
    • Current instrument status
  5. Notify Laboratory Manager with complete documentation

CRITICAL: Before contacting Technical Quality Specialist and Lab Manager, ensure you have documented all troubleshooting steps and obtained the reference number from Tech Support.

When to Perform Automated Analysis

Automated urinalysis is the preferred method when:

  • Sufficient specimen volume available (≥2.0 mL for CLINITEK Novus)
  • CLINITEK Novus system is operational
  • Specimen meets acceptability criteria

Calibration Completion Steps:

  1. Select [Start] and the screen will count down from 3:13 to zero
  2. The analyzer updates the progress of the run
  3. Select [Exit] to return to the system menu
  4. If calibration passes, the status bar will return to "Ready", and the system will be ready to process quality control and patient samples

CLINITEK Novus Operation

System Status Verification:

  1. Confirm all CV-11 status indicator LED lights are illuminated and green
  2. Ensure the Novus is ready for testing with "Ready" displayed on the Home screen status bar
  3. If the system displays "Not Ready", review the messages in the Status Log. Complete the necessary troubleshooting to bring the system to "Ready" status:
    • Yellow messages - A yellow warning message requires you to take action
    • White messages - A white warning message indicates that a warning exists
  4. Check the status of the reagent cards. If necessary, load a new reagent cassette
  5. Check the supply of rinse, the external rinse bottle is present, the bottle must be manually inspected
  6. Check the card waste container and the liquid waste container. Empty, if necessary
  7. Check the paper supply in the printer

Sample preparation:

  1. Mix each sample thoroughly by inversion
  2. Do not test samples that are visibly bloody, mucoid, or foamy
  3. Pour 2-6 mL into labeled plastic centrifuge tube
  4. Ensure minimum 2 mL volume for analysis
  5. Prepare a well-mixed urine sample into a clean sample tube labelled with the appropriate barcode

Instrument operation:

  1. Place tube(s) in rack with barcode visible within the rack opening
  2. Load the rack with the groove to the right onto the right sampler pool
  3. Follow instrument prompts for analysis
  4. Results automatically transmitted to LIS
  5. Remove tube after analysis complete

UF-5000 Automated Particle Analysis

Sample preparation:

  • Use same tube from CLINITEK Novus analysis
  • Ensure adequate volume remaining (minimum 1 mL)
  • Check for excessive turbidity before analysis

Analysis process:

  • Place sample in UF-5000 sample rack
  • Barcode facing outward through rack slot
  • Analyzer performs automated microscopic analysis
  • Results include cell counts, bacteria, casts

Auto-Verification Rules

[Reference: KP SOP 15336_1 Section 6.8]

Specimens meeting ALL criteria below may auto-verify:

  • Clarity: Clear or Slightly Cloudy
  • Color: Yellow or Amber
  • Specific Gravity: 1.003-1.030
  • pH: 5.0-8.0
  • Protein: Negative to Trace
  • Glucose: Negative
  • Ketones: Negative to Trace
  • Blood: Negative to Trace
  • Nitrite: Negative
  • Leukocyte Esterase: Negative to Trace
  • WBC: <5/hpf
  • RBC: <3/hpf
  • No critical crystals or casts

Flags Requiring Review

[Reference: KP SOP 15336_1 Section 6.9]

  • Review Flag: Abnormal formed elements detected
  • Atypical Cells: Possible malignant cells
  • Path Cast: Pathological casts detected
  • YLC (Yeast-Like Cells): >5/hpf
  • Crystals: Abnormal crystals present
  • Conductivity Error: Invalid specific gravity

Result Review Process

Reviewing results on UDM (Urinalysis Data Manager):

  1. Touch [Results List] button on toolbar or Main screen to bring up 'Results Confirmation List' screen
  2. Select result line to be reviewed
  3. Select [Details] button
  4. The 'Analysis' Tab contains results, additional flagging information and review comments
  5. Select [Review Comment] area if multiple comments exist
  6. Check the details
  7. Select [Close]
  8. In the [Explorer] screen, select the analysis result for which you want to check details
  9. Select the [Browser] button on the toolbar
  10. Select a tab to check analysis result details

Reviewing results on Novus:

  1. Each sample is assigned a status:
    • Sieve: samples that need confirmation or microscopic review
    • Error: samples that had errors (dispense error, low volume, etc.)
    • Send Error: Samples that could not be sent to the LIS
  2. Select [Print Summary] to print end-of-run report that includes sample IDs and status
  3. Select [Print] to print the patient reports for samples (only available on standalone instrument)
  4. Select [Send] to transmit results to LIS
  5. Select [View] to see results for the first sample listed
  6. Review flagged results and analyte flags. A symbol representing analyte flag appears next to results that meet the flagging criteria
  7. Select the back button to return to the Patient Results screen
  8. Select [Exit] to return to the Home screen

Manual Microscopy Procedures

[Reference: KP SOP 15336_1 Section 6.12]

When Manual Review is Required

  • Analyzer flags for review
  • Discrepancy between chemistry and microscopy
  • Physician specifically requests manual review
  • QC or proficiency testing samples
  • Crystals requiring identification

Manual Microscopy Procedure

  1. Centrifuge 12 mL urine at 400 RCF for 5 minutes
  2. Decant supernatant leaving 0.5-1.0 mL
  3. Resuspend sediment by gentle mixing
  4. Place drop on slide and coverslip
  5. Examine under microscope:
    • 10x for casts and overall assessment
    • 40x for detailed examination
    • Count 10 fields and average
  6. Report as per hpf (40x) or lpf (10x)

Manual Urinalysis

Indications for Manual Testing

Perform manual dipstick analysis only when:

  • CLINITEK Novus is out of service
  • Specimen volume is <2.0 mL
  • Specimen is grossly bloody
  • Specimen has visible particles or is mucoid
  • Specimen quantity is insufficient (QNS) for automated analysis

Procedure Steps

IMPORTANT NOTE: For grossly bloody urine, cancel the dipstick test with comment: "Unable to read due to color of urine. See Microscopic"
  1. Quality control first:
    • Run Quantimetrix Dipper controls before patient testing
    • Verify all QC results are acceptable
    • Document QC results on log sheet
  2. Patient sample preparation:
    • Mix specimen thoroughly by inversion
    • Pour adequate volume into clean container
    • Note and document color and clarity
  3. Pre-analytical Steps:
    • Do not remove strip from bottle until immediately before use
    • Replace cap immediately and tightly after removing reagent strip
    • If desiccant packet removed from Multistix 10SG bottle, discard bottle and use fresh bottle
  4. Dipstick testing procedure:
    • Remove ONE Multistix-10SG strip from bottle
    • Immediately recap bottle to prevent moisture exposure
    • Immerse ALL reagent pads completely in urine
    • Remove immediately and tap edge to remove excess
    • Hold strip horizontally to prevent reagent mixing

Critical Timing for Dipstick Reading

Parameter Reading Time
Glucose, Bilirubin 30 seconds
Ketones 40 seconds
Blood, pH, Protein 60 seconds
Urobilinogen, Nitrites 60 seconds
Leukocyte Esterase 2 minutes
  1. Reading results:
    • Compare each pad to color chart at specified times
    • Read in good lighting (not fluorescent)
    • Match closest color block for each parameter
    • Record results immediately on log sheet
  2. Data entry:
    • Enter results in LIS system
    • Convert glucose from mg/dL to g/dL if needed
    • Include color and clarity observations
    • Add appropriate comments

Parameters Readable Despite Color Interference

When color interference affects reagent strip readings, the following parameters can still be recorded:

  • Specific Gravity (SG) - Distinct color changes readable despite interference
  • pH - Distinct color changes readable despite interference
  • Color - Visual assessment of urine specimen
  • Clarity - Visual assessment (clear, hazy, cloudy, turbid)
  • All microscopic findings - Independent of chemical reagent reactions

Parameters Affected by Color Interference

The following chemical parameters may be reported as "unable to read due to color interference":

  • Protein
  • Glucose
  • Ketones
  • Blood
  • Bilirubin
  • Urobilinogen
  • Nitrite
  • Leukocyte esterase

Specific Gravity

Sample analysis:

  • Use dipstick method as part of manual analysis
  • Read specific gravity pad according to manufacturer's instructions
  • Report to nearest 0.005 increment

14. CALCULATIONS AND RESULT REPORTING

Result Reporting Format

Chemical Analysis Results:

  • Report as negative, trace, 1+, 2+, 3+, 4+
  • Include units where applicable (pH: 5.0-9.0)
  • Specific gravity: 1.003-1.030

Microscopic Results:

  • RBC/WBC: #/hpf
  • Casts: type and #/lpf
  • Crystals: type and quantity
  • Bacteria: few, moderate, many

Correlation Requirements

Review for Discrepancies:

  • Positive blood on dipstick but no RBCs microscopically → Consider myoglobin/hemoglobin
  • Positive leukocyte esterase but no WBCs → Consider lysis in alkaline urine
  • Many bacteria but negative nitrite → Consider non-nitrite producing organisms

Manual Microscopic Examination

Procedure Steps

  1. Sample preparation:
    • Centrifuge specimen at 3000 RPM for 5 minutes
    • Decant supernatant into stainless steel sink
    • Resuspend sediment in remaining supernatant using pipette
  2. Slide preparation:
    • Deliver one drop of sediment into clean well of DeciSlide Counting Chamber
    • Allow sediment to settle at least 15 seconds before analysis
    • NOTE: Samples with excessive sediment may require evaluation using microscope slide and cover slip
  3. Microscopic examination:
    • Using 10X objective (Low Power Field - LPF):
      • Scan approximately 10 fields
      • Determine amount or number per field for:
        • Mucus threads
        • All casts
      • Enter results in Urinalysis Data Manager (UDM)
    • Using 40X objective (High Power Field - HPF):
      • Scan approximately 10 fields
      • Determine average amount or number per field for:
        • RBC
        • WBC
        • Epithelial cells
        • Bacteria
        • All crystals
        • Other constituents (e.g., Yeast, Trichomonas, Sperm in males only)
      • Enter results in Urinalysis Data Manager (UDM)
  4. Special Procedures:
    • Amorphous Urate crystal identification: Crystals dissolve upon addition of appropriate reagents

Microscopic Reporting Guidelines

Element Quantification Reporting Format
RBCs, WBCs Count per HPF 0-2, 3-5, 6-10, 11-25, 26-50, >50
Epithelial cells Count per HPF Few, moderate, many
Bacteria Estimate per HPF None, few, moderate, many
Casts Count per LPF 0-1, 2-5, 6-10, >10
Crystals Estimate per LPF Few, moderate, many (identify type)
Mucus threads Estimate per LPF None, few, moderate, many

Crystal Identification

  • Acid urine crystals: Uric acid, calcium oxalate, amorphous urates
  • Alkaline urine crystals: Triple phosphate, calcium phosphate, amorphous phosphates
  • Pathological crystals: Cystine, leucine, tyrosine, cholesterol
  • Drug crystals: Sulfa, ampicillin (note medication history)
  • Amorphous Crystal Test: Follow established laboratory protocol for crystal identification.

16. CRITICAL VALUES

Critical Values Requiring Immediate Notification

Finding Critical Level Clinical Significance
Glucose ≥2+ with ketones Possible diabetic ketoacidosis
RBC casts Any present Glomerulonephritis
WBC casts Any present Pyelonephritis/interstitial nephritis
Pathological crystals Cystine, tyrosine, leucine Metabolic disorders
Gross hematuria 4+ blood Significant bleeding

Notification Procedure:

  1. Verify result by repeat analysis or review
  2. Contact ordering physician or nurse immediately
  3. Document notification in LIS:
    • Date and time
    • Person notified
    • Results communicated
    • Read-back verification

Result Interpretation and Reporting

Automated Result Verification

Auto-verification criteria:

  • All QC within acceptable limits
  • No instrument flags or errors
  • Results within established parameters
  • No critical values requiring manual review

Manual review required for:

  • Critical values
  • Instrument flags or error messages
  • Discrepant dipstick vs. microscopic results
  • Unusual microscopic findings

Specimens Flagged for Abnormality - Microbiology Referral

When urine specimens flag for abnormality requiring microbiological analysis:

  • Transfer specimen to Grey Top tube
  • Send to Rockville for Microbiology Analysis
  • Document referral in LIS with appropriate comments
  • Ensure proper labeling and chain of custody

Common Result Patterns and Interpretations

Pattern Findings Likely Cause
UTI Pattern Positive nitrites, LE, bacteria, WBCs Bacterial urinary tract infection
Kidney Disease Protein, RBCs, casts, specific gravity fixed Glomerular or tubular disease
Diabetes Glucose, ketones, high specific gravity Diabetic ketoacidosis or hyperglycemia
Liver Disease Bilirubin positive, increased urobilinogen Hepatic dysfunction or obstruction
Hemolysis Blood positive, no RBCs microscopically Intravascular hemolysis
Contamination Many squamous epithelial cells, mixed bacteria Poor collection technique

17. LIMITATIONS AND INTERFERENCES

Known Interferences

Test False Positive False Negative
Protein Alkaline urine (pH >8), quaternary ammonium compounds Dilute urine, Bence-Jones proteins
Glucose Bleach, peroxide contamination High specific gravity, ascorbic acid
Blood Myoglobin, bleach, bacterial peroxidases Ascorbic acid, high nitrite
Ketones L-dopa metabolites, captopril Improper storage
Bilirubin Phenazopyridine, rifampin Light exposure, ascorbic acid
Nitrite Pigmented specimens Non-nitrate diet, non-reducing bacteria
Leukocyte esterase Vaginal contamination High glucose, high protein, antibiotics

Method Limitations:

  • Does not detect light chains (Bence-Jones proteins)
  • May not detect early renal disease
  • Specific gravity by dipstick affected by protein
  • Crystals identification requires expertise
  • Cannot differentiate RBC morphology on dipstick

18. EMERGENCY PROCEDURES

⚠️ EMERGENCY PROCEDURES

When All Automated Systems Are Down

  1. Assess situation: Determine expected downtime
  2. Contact immediate support: Notify Laboratory Managers and Laboratory Directors with Service Reference number
  3. Prioritize samples: Process STAT and urgent urinalysis samples first
  4. Use manual methods: Consider sending to reference lab or backup analyzer
  5. Document everything: Keep detailed records of all actions
  6. Call for help: Contact service representatives and managers
  7. Communicate delays: Inform requesting physicians of delays

Contamination Incidents

  1. Immediate containment: Isolate affected area
  2. Personal protection: Ensure staff safety with PPE
  3. Stop testing: Halt all operations in affected area
  4. Clean and disinfect: Use appropriate disinfectants
  5. Contact support: Notify Laboratory Managers and Laboratory Directors
  6. Document incident: Complete incident report
  7. Restart procedures: Only after thorough decontamination

Power Failure Response

  1. Secure samples: Ensure proper storage temperature (2-8°C)
  2. Document time: Record exact time of power failure
  3. Check emergency power: Verify backup systems operational
  4. Preserve reagents: Maintain cold chain if possible
  5. Contact support: Notify Laboratory Managers and Laboratory Directors
  6. Recovery planning: Prepare for system restart procedures

Instrument Failure - Sysmex Analyzers

  1. Switch to backup Sysmex analyzer if available
  2. Use manual dipstick reading:
    • Dip strip in urine for 2 seconds
    • Remove excess urine
    • Read at specified time intervals
    • Compare to color chart
  3. Use refractometer for specific gravity
  4. Continue microscopic examination manually
  5. Contact service for repair

Reagent Shortage

  • Check for expired but usable reagents (verify with QC)
  • Borrow from sister facilities
  • Prioritize STAT and critical specimens
  • Send to reference lab if necessary

22. DOWNTIME PROCEDURES

IMPORTANT: Instrument Downtime or Issues Running Specimens

If the automated urinalysis instruments are down or there are issues running a specimen, send to MOB lab or send to other regional laboratory with a working instrument. Use the alphabetical file to keep track of requisitions received.

Emergency Procedures for Urinalysis

When Urinalysis Analyzer Is Down:

  1. Assess situation: Determine expected downtime
  2. Contact immediate support: Notify Laboratory Managers and Laboratory Directors with Service Reference number
  3. Prioritize samples: Process STAT and urgent urinalysis samples first
  4. Use manual methods: Manual dipstick and microscopy or send to reference lab/MOB backup analyzer
  5. Document everything: Keep detailed records of all actions
  6. Call for help: Contact service representatives and managers
  7. Communicate delays: Inform requesting physicians of delays

Backup Testing Options

Test Manual Method Backup Location Priority
Urinalysis Manual dipstick + microscopy MOB Laboratory STAT first
Urine Microscopy Manual microscopy In-house manual All priorities
Specific Gravity Refractometer In-house backup All priorities
Urine Culture Setup Manual setup In-house procedure All priorities

Primary Backup: Manual Methods (Sysmex UN Downtime)

  1. Manual Dipstick Reading
    • Use Sysmex UC test strips with visual reader chart
    • Or backup Multistix® 10 SG strips
    • Follow manufacturer's timing exactly
    • Document as manual method in downtime log
  2. Refractometer for Specific Gravity
    • Calibrate with distilled water
    • Use 1 drop of urine
    • Read at eye level
  3. Continue Microscopy
    • Process as normal
    • May need to increase volume examined

LIS Downtime Operations

Error Message Management During LIS Downtime

Error messages on instruments when running patients during LIS downtime are okay because:

  1. Expected behavior - The instruments are correctly detecting and reporting the loss of LIS connectivity, which confirms the system is working as designed
  2. Operations can continue - Most modern laboratory instruments can operate in standalone mode during LIS downtime, allowing patient testing to proceed despite the connection error
  3. Results are preserved - Instruments typically store results locally in their internal memory during downtime, preventing data loss
  4. Downtime procedures activated - The error message serves as a clear indicator to staff that downtime protocols should be followed (manual result recording, downtime logs, etc.)
  5. No actual malfunction - The error reflects a known, temporary communication issue rather than an instrument failure, so patient testing accuracy is not compromised
  6. Recovery is straightforward - Once LIS connectivity is restored, the stored results can usually be transmitted automatically or manually uploaded

High-Demand Laboratory Operations During Downtime

To maintain patient testing efficiency during LIS downtime:

  • Continue testing on all instruments despite error messages
  • Use manual logging to track all specimens tested
  • Print instrument results immediately after testing
  • Maintain chronological order of testing for proper recovery
  • Communicate delays to requesting departments
  • Prioritize STAT and urgent specimens
  • Follow established downtime workflows to minimize disruption

The error message serves as a clear indicator to staff that the LIS is unavailable, allowing them to follow established downtime procedures while maintaining testing capabilities. This ensures continuous patient care despite system limitations.

Downtime Protocol

Pre-ordered specimens that were received in the lab before the computer system downtime:

  • Can be processed as normal
  • Results will be held in UDM until the LIS is up
  • Print results and call critical action values per lab policy

Pre-order samples that were not received in the lab before the downtime:

  • Can be processed as normal if the order is in UDM
  • Place these samples in a holding rack, as they may need to be received after the system downtime
  • If there is no order in UDM proceed to step 3

All samples received after the start of the computer downtime with no order on the UDM or with a downtime label:

Will need to be ordered on the UDM before testing:

  • a. At the UDM select Search icon
  • b. Click edit
  • c. Scan or enter specimen number
  • d. Click the test selection, choose test to be analyzed
  • e. Click Save
  • f. Click OK
  • g. Click Save
  • h. Load sample on analyzer and perform the requested test

Review results according to lab policy

Print results from the UDM:

  • Call Critical Action values per lab policy

Complete all testing for a specimen before proceeding to downtime recovery:

  • This includes selecting a rerun or performing microscopic
  • From UDM screen, click output on top right, then click Report (GP) to print the results
  • Click host output to send the results to LIS after everything comes back up
  • Note: Results must be validated to print

Simplified Downtime Specimen Labeling Procedures

Step 1: Order Retrieval and Preparation

  1. For NON-URGENT CARE patients: Lab reception staff will retrieve all orders from KPHC system
  2. For UC/CDU members testing: DOWNTIME ORDER FORMS for STAT Testing ONLY
  3. Label preparation: Specimen Processors need to prepare HAND WRITTEN CERNER DOWNTIME LABELS for each tube/sample if Cerner preprinted labels are not available for additional tubes/samples

Required Information on ALL Labels:

  • CERNER NUMBER
  • Patient's Name
  • Medical Record #
  • Test, collection time, initials

Step 2: Label Application (Choose appropriate method)

Method A - Primary tube (not shared/processed/aliquoted):
  1. Write test/test group and tube type on both large and small labels
  2. Attach the large label to the primary tube assuring the name and MRN of the patient are visible on the tube. If the patient's name and MRN are not visible, prepare HAND WRITTEN CERNER DOWNTIME LABELS for each tubes/samples if Cerner preprinted labels are not available for additional tubes/samples
  3. Initial the label
  4. Place a small label on the requisition beside the test or group of tests associated with the tube
Method B - Primary tube (for tests that must be spun, shared or split):
  1. Write the Patient's name, MRN, TEST, and tube type on the large label
  2. Write the test(s) name and tube type on the small labels
  3. Attach the small label to the primary tube
  4. Place a small label on the requisition next to the test or test group associated with that tube
  5. Example: CMP, MAG and SOSM (2 labels needed)
    • 1st label will only have CMP and MAG
    • 2nd label will only have SOSM
    • Both small labels will be placed on primary tube
Method C - Extra tubes:
  1. Place the "Extra tube" sticker on the tube
  2. Place the tube and a copy of the requisition in the bag
  3. Place the bag in the "Extra Tube Bin" or deliver it to the analyzing area

Extra Tube Label - Apply this sticker to extra tubes

Step 3: Sample Collection and Processing

  1. After sample collection:
    • STAT Samples: Along with completed worksheet goes directly to Lab Technologist for immediate processing and follow up
    • ROUTINE samples: Along with completed worksheet go to sample processor
  2. STAT Processing:
    • Lab Technologist will distribute samples to different benches as needed
    • Ensure all tests are performed, resulted and called/faxed by the performing technologist
    • Once all tests are completed, attach analyzer printouts to corresponding worksheets. Make 2 copies of the results, file one in the downtime file in alphabetical order by last name. Result worksheets can be faxed or tubed down to UC/CDU and other department. Store all samples with SAME CERNER NUMBER (One patient) together.
  3. ROUTINE Processing:
    • Sample processor will process all the samples, centrifuge them and store routines them appropriately and run the STATS on the instruments. All samples with SAME CERNER NUMBER (One patient) should be grouped together

Step 4: System Recovery

  1. When computer system is restored:
    • All orders need to be processed in CERNER with proper collection/receive time (Specimen Log-in)
    • Labels must be pulled
    • Sample processor with help of other phlebotomists on duty process, label and track each sample collected during downtime to RLR/Quest etc.
  2. Completed sample processing:
    • Lab Technologist processes all DONE samples
    • Pull labels and perform Specimen Log-in with actual collection/receive time
    • Result them in Cerner with help of other techs on duty
    • IMPORTANT: Process all patients specimens together. DO NOT SEPARATE ORDERS. All patient specimens must be processed together

Additional Downtime Steps

  • Extra Tubes, Place the "Extra tube" Sticker on the tube and file in downtime rack
  • When all tubes are labeled, highlight the test codes on requisition and double check for missed tests
  • Make one (1) copy of the Requisition for each label plus one
  • Place one (1) copy of the requisition, one (1) specimen tube, and all associated labels to the appropriate bench
  • Place the original requisition in the Processing alphabetical downtime file bin

Processing samples:

  1. Centrifuge samples as usual
  2. Check the information on the requisition against that on the primary tube and associated labels
  3. If all is correct, proceed to make aliquots following our normal processing procedure
    • Label appropriate processing containers with a large label. Initial and aliquot sample as usual
    • Place extra little labels
    • Deliver the specimens and a copy of the requisition for each test to the correct analyzing bench per lab protocol

Once the specimens are ran file in the downtime rack. Place the "Extra tube" Sticker on the tube and file in downtime rack

Once the computer system is up, all orders needs to be processed in CERNER with proper collection/receive time (Specimen Log-in) and all testing completed.

Extended Downtime (>4 hours)

  • Send specimens to backup laboratory (MOB Lab or Regional Lab)
  • Kaiser Permanente Regional Lab: 1-800-XXX-XXXX
  • Maintain chain of custody
  • Track all sent specimens using alphabetical file
  • Document all actions in downtime log
